## Second-Year Priority Agenda — Specific and Accountable

The capstone sections have identified second-year priorities in each functional area. Day 97 organizes them into a coherent agenda with the prioritization rationale that connects each priority to the risk register, the POA&M, and the program's current gaps.

---

### Priority 1 — Complete CP-2 Authorization Condition (Immediate)

**What:** Milestones 3 and 4 of the contingency plan development. Milestone 3 requires the clinical leadership approval meeting with all three participants confirmed. Milestone 4 requires the final CP-2 document signed, paper downtime forms designed and reviewed by clinical staff for usability, and forms physically posted at clinical workstations.

**Why first:** This is the only open authorization condition. Missing the deadline triggers mandatory AO re-authorization evaluation. The clinical downtime forms — the physical artifact that makes the CP-2 actually operational, not just documented — do not yet exist. A contingency plan that exists as a document but has no paper forms available at the workstations is not a plan that clinical staff can execute at 2am.

**Success indicator:** Paper downtime forms posted at all clinical workstations. Health IT Manager and Clinical Director signatures on CP-2 v1.0. ISSO notifies AO of condition completion.

---

### Priority 2 — AU-12 Denied Access Logging Remediation (90 Days)

**What:** Investigate the OpenMRS audit log module configuration to determine whether denied access events can be captured through configuration change. If so, implement and verify. If an application limitation, implement a CloudWatch metric filter on access denial HTTP response codes as a compensating control that provides partial coverage.

**Why second:** This is the program's only Moderate-severity open finding. It affects detection capability for two risk scenarios — RS-001 (credential probing before successful access) and RS-005 (insider probing outside role scope). It was self-identified, which is a program maturity indicator, but it remains a genuine gap that reduces the forensic capability the SAR documented as compliant.

**Success indicator:** Semi-annual audit log completeness test passes for denied access event type. POA&M item closed with documented remediation evidence. Security Hub AU-12 control status updated.

---

### Priority 3 — Phishing Simulation Program Launch (Q2)

**What:** GoPhish self-hosted deployment; quarterly simulation cadence; aggregate results reporting to Health IT Manager; Q1 baseline measurement with no target; Q4 target below 10% click rate and above 30% reporting rate.

**Why third:** RS-001 and RS-004 are both HIGH-rated based on HC3 threat intelligence identifying phishing as the primary attack vector for organizations matching MyClinic's profile. The training completion metric (KPI-AT-1, 100%) confirms implementation but not effectiveness. The phishing simulation is the only mechanism that tests whether the training has produced behavioral change under realistic conditions.

**Success indicator:** First simulation executed in Q2. Baseline click rate and reporting rate documented. Q3 and Q4 simulations executed. Trend established by end of second year.

---

### Priority 4 — IR-3 Tabletop Exercise (Before Re-Authorization Assessment)

**What:** Tabletop exercise with 2am/primary-contact-unreachable scenario. Participants: ISSO, IT Administrator, Health IT Manager. Post-tabletop: IRP updated to explicitly document IT Administrator's 15-minute escalation path when ISSO is unreachable.

**Why fourth:** The IRP documents a ransomware response capability. The RDS architectural separation limits the damage radius. The pre-authorized EC2 isolation action removes the decision bottleneck. But none of this has been tested under time pressure with a realistic scenario designed to find the gap the IRP does not fully address. The tabletop is what converts documented readiness into demonstrated readiness.

**Success indicator:** Tabletop executed, debrief documented, IRP updated with gap identified by scenario. Completed before re-authorization assessment window.

---

### Priority 5 — Policy Suite Development (Second Half of Year Two)

**What:** Three standalone policy documents — Acceptable Use Policy, Change Management Policy, and Data Retention and Disposal Policy — developed as organizational governance documents with owners, acknowledgment requirements, and review cycles.

**Why fifth (not higher):** The policies are important but the risks they address are currently managed through compensating mechanisms: IS-AC-001 covers the most critical access control obligations (shared credential prohibition, MFA requirement), CM-3 is documented in the SSP, and retention obligations are captured in the SSP narrative. The first four priorities address gaps with immediate risk implications. The policy development addresses the organizational governance completeness gap that matters for re-authorization but is not creating immediate control effectiveness gaps.

**Sequencing:** AUP first (RS-005 insider threat deterrence connection), Change Management Policy second (M-002/A-7 pattern and IT Administrator acknowledgment), Data Retention and Disposal Policy third (institutional continuity and data steward designation).

**Success indicator:** All three policies developed, reviewed by Health IT Manager and AO, acknowledged by all applicable staff, added to annual review cycle.

---

### Priority 6 — RPO Reduction (Second-Year Budget Cycle)

**What:** Daily S3 backup export replacing weekly export, reducing maximum RPO from 7 days to 1 day for complete environment reconstruction. Proposal under development for AO and Health IT Manager approval and budget consideration.

**Why sixth:** The current backup architecture passed the Q1 restoration test and meets the defined RTO. The RPO improvement is a genuine risk reduction for RS-007 and the worst-case ransomware data loss scenario, but it is not addressing an immediate gap. It belongs in the second-year planning cycle as a budget and prioritization conversation, not as an emergency remediation.

**Success indicator:** Proposal presented to AO with cost estimate and risk reduction rationale. Decision documented (approve/defer). If approved, implementation and test completed before end of second year.

