## Final Note

97 days. One healthcare NGO. One open-source EHR. One cloud environment. One complete GRC program cycle — from initial system registration through FIPS 199 categorization, control selection, SSP development, formal assessment, conditional ATO, eight months of continuous monitoring, Q1 findings, compliance mapping, risk register evolution, incident response playbooks, training program design, a full capstone synthesis, and an annual AO briefing with honest gaps and specific asks.

The next step is not Day 98. The next step is executing the second-year priority agenda — completing CP-2, remediating AU-12, launching the phishing simulation, executing the IR-3 tabletop, developing the three missing policies, and proposing the RPO reduction. Every one of those steps has a target date, an owner, and a success criterion. That is what 97 days of GRC discipline looks like in practice.

If you are reading this on the same GRC path — at Day 5 or Day 50 or Day 90 — the most useful thing I can tell you is this: do the work specifically. Name the real system, the real controls, the real gaps, the real people making the real decisions. The specificity is not just a writing discipline. It is the entire point.

